    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1916-05-02T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1916-05-02T00:00:00-05:00" n="490"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d490">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 300.115/8363</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul General at London</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_SRP1"
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Skinner</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 1739</seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1916-05-02">
                            <hi rend="italic">May 2, 1916</hi>
                        </date>.<lb/>[<hi rend="italic">Received May 13</hi>.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have the honor to enclose herewith in duplicate
                    list of goods consigned by various American firms to importers in Holland in
                    care of the Netherlands Oversea Trust, and now returned for prize court
                        proceedings.<note n="1" xml:id="d490fn1">Not printed.</note>
                </p>
                <p>The attention of the Department is called very particularly to the fact that the
                    British authorities appear to have decided to ignore the pledge expressed in a
                    note dated April 27, 1915,<note n="2" xml:id="d490fn2">
                        <ref target="frus1915Supp#pg_378">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1915, Supplement, p.
                        378</ref>.</note> to the Ambassador, stating that “while His Majesty’s
                    Government do not require cargoes to be consigned to the Netherlands Oversea
                    Trust, they do accept consignment in that form as proof that the cargo is
                    intended for <hi rend="italic">bona fide</hi> consumption in Holland.”</p>
                <p>I have [etc.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_SRP1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Robert P. Skinner</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
